          "correctOptionId": "opt-1",
          "explanation": "Ans. is 'a' i.e., Spring Cattarrh * Cobble-stone or pavement stone appearance is seen in spring catarrh.Important signs of spring catarrhConjunctivalCornealPalpebralBulbar# Punctate epithelial keratitis# Ulcerative vernal keratitis: shallow transverse ulcer (Shield ulcer)# Vernal corneal plaques# Subepithelial scarring# Pseudogerontoxon: chracterized by a classical \"cupid's bow\" outline.* Papillary hypertrophy into polygonal papilla* Cobble stone (Pavement stone) appearance* Giant papilla (Cauliflower excrescence)* Gelatinous thickening around limbus* Horner trantas spots* Dusky red triangular congestion* Follicles are not seen in spring catarrh.",
